# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boto3-aws
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon announced a limited public beta test of EC2 on August 25, 2006, offering access on a first-come, first-served basis.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon added two new instance types (Large and Extra-Large) on October 16, 2007.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On May 29, 2008, two more types were added, High-CPU Medium and High-CPU Extra Large.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] There were twelve types of instances available.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon added three new features on March 27, 2008: static IP addresses, availability zones, and user-selectable kernels.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On August 20, 2008, Amazon added Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] This provides persistent storage, a feature that had been lacking since the service was introduced.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon EC2 went into full production when it dropped the beta label on October 23, 2008.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] These features were subsequently added on May 18, 2009.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon EC2 was developed mostly by a team in Cape Town, South Africa led by Chris Pinkham.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Pinkham provided the initial architecture guidance for EC2 and then built the team and led the development of the project along with Willem van Biljon.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Initially, EC2 used Xen virtualization exclusively.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] However, on November 6, 2017, Amazon announced the new C5 family of instances that were based on a custom architecture around the KVM hypervisor, called Nitro.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Each virtual machine, called an "instance", functions as a virtual private server.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon sizes instances based on "Elastic Compute Units".
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The performance of otherwise identical virtual machines may vary.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On November 28, 2017, AWS announced a bare-metal instance, a departure from exclusively offering virtualized instance types.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] As of April 2018, Amazon charged about $0.0058 per hour ($4.176 per month) for the smallest "Nano Instance" (t2.nano) virtual machine running Linux or Windows.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Storage-optimized instances cost as much as $4.992 per hour (i3.16xlarge).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] "Reserved" instances can go as low as $2.50 per month for a three-year prepaid plan.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The data transfer charge ranges from free to $0.12 per gigabyte, depending on the direction and monthly volume (inbound data transfer is free on all AWS services).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EC2 costs can be analyzed using the Amazon Cost and Usage Report.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] There are many different cost categories for EC2 including: hourly Instance Charges, Data Transfer, EBS Volumes, EBS Volume Snapshots, and Nat Gateway.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] As of December 2010 Amazon offered a bundle of free resource credits to new account holders.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The credits are designed to run a "micro" sized server, storage (EBS), and bandwidth for one year.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Unused credits cannot be carried over from one month to the next.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Reserved instances enable EC2 or RDS service users to reserve an instance for one or three years.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The corresponding hourly rate charged by Amazon to operate the instance is 35 to 75% lower than the rate charged for on-demand instances.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Reserved instances can be purchased with three different payment options: All Upfront, Partial Upfront and No Upfront.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The different purchase options allow for different structuring of payment models, with a larger discount given to customers that pay their reservation upfront.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Reserved Instances are purchased based on a resource commitment.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] These reservations are made based on an instance type and a count of that instance type.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] For example, you could reserve 100 i3.large instances for a 3-year term.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In September 2016, AWS announced several enhancements to Reserved instances, introducing a new feature called scope and a new reservation type called a Convertible.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In October 2017, AWS announced the allowance to subdivide the instances purchased for more flexibility.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Cloud providers maintain large amounts of excess capacity they have to sell or risk incurring losses.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon EC2 Spot instances are spare compute capacity in the AWS cloud available at up to 90% discount compared to On-Demand prices.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] As a trade-off, AWS offers no SLA on these instances and customers take the risk that it can be interrupted with only two minutes of notification when Amazon needs the capacity back.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Researchers from the Israeli Institute of Technology found that "they (Spot instances) are typically generated at random from within a tight price interval via a dynamic hidden reserve price".
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Some companies, like Spotinst, are using machine learning to predict spot interruptions up to 15 minutes in advance.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In November 2019, Amazon announced Savings Plans.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Savings Plans are an alternative to Reserved Instances that come in two different plan types: Compute Savings Plans and EC2 Instances Savings Plans.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Compute Savings Plans allow an organization to commit to EC2 and Fargate usage with the freedom to change region, family, size, availability zone, OS and tenancy inside the lifespan of the commitment.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EC2 Instance Savings plans provide a larger discount than Compute Savings Plans but are less flexible meaning a user must commit to individual instance families within a region to take advantage, but with the freedom to change instances within the family in that region.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] AWS uses the Cost Explorer to automatically calculate recommendations for the commitments you should make how that commitment will look like as a monthly charge on your AWS bill.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] AWS Savings Plans are purchased based on hourly spend commitment.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] This hourly commitment is made using the discounted pricing of the savings plan you are purchasing.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] For example, you could commit to spending $5 per hour, on a Compute Savings Plan, for a 3-year term.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] When it launched in August 2006, the EC2 service offered Linux and later Sun Microsystems' OpenSolaris and Solaris Express Community Edition.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In October 2008, EC2 added the Windows Server 2003 and Windows Server 2008 operating systems to the list of available operating systems.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In March 2011, NetBSD AMIs became available.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In November 2012, Windows Server 2012 support was added.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Since 2006, Colin Percival, a FreeBSD developer and Security Officer, solicited Amazon to add FreeBSD.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In November 2012, Amazon officially supported running FreeBSD in EC2.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The FreeBSD/EC2 platform is maintained by Percival who also developed the secure deduplicating Amazon S3-cloud based backup service Tarsnap.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon has their own Linux distribution based on Fedora and Red Hat Enterprise Linux as a low cost offering known as the Amazon Linux AMI.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Version 2013.03 included: Linux kernel, Java OpenJDK Runtime Environment and GNU Compiler Collection.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On November 30, 2020, Amazon announced that it would be adding macOS to the EC2 service.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Initial support was announced for macOS Mojave and macOS Catalina running on Mac Mini.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon Elastic Container Registry (ECR) is a Docker registry service for Amazon EC2 instances to access repositories and images.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (EKS) a managed Kubernetes service running on top of EC2 without needing to provision or manage instances.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] An EC2 instance may be launched with a choice of two types of storage for its boot disk or "root device." The first option is a local "instance-store" disk as a root device (originally the only choice).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The second option is to use an EBS volume as a root device.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Instance-store volumes are temporary storage, which survive rebooting an EC2 instance, but when the instance is stopped or terminated (e.g., by an API call, or due to a failure), this store is lost.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS) provides raw block devices that can be attached to Amazon EC2 instances.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] These block devices can then be used like any raw block device.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In a typical use case, this would include formatting the device with a filesystem and mounting it.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In addition, EBS supports a number of advanced storage features, including snapshotting and cloning.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EBS volumes are built on replicated storage, so that the failure of a single component will not cause data loss.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EBS was introduced to the general public by Amazon in August 2008.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EBS volumes provide persistent storage independent of the lifetime of the EC2 instance, and act much like hard drives on a real server.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] More accurately, they appear as block devices to the operating system that are backed by Amazon's disk arrays.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The OS is free to use the device however it wants.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In the most common case, a file system is loaded and the volume acts as a hard drive.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Another possible use is the creation of RAID arrays by combining two or more EBS volumes.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] RAID allows increases of speed and/or reliability of EBS.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Users can set up and manage storage volumes of sizes from 1 GB to 16 TB.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The volumes support snapshots, which can be taken from a GUI tool or the API.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EBS volumes can be attached or detached from instances while they are running, and moved from one instance to another.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Simple Storage Service (S3) is a storage system in which data is accessible to EC2 instances, or directly over the network to suitably authenticated callers (all communication is over HTTP).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon does not charge for the bandwidth for communications between EC2 instances and S3 storage "in the same region." Accessing S3 data stored in a different region (for example, data stored in Europe from a US East Coast EC2 instance) will be billed at Amazon's normal rates.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] S3-based storage is priced per gigabyte per month.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] For example, Apache Hadoop supports a special s3: filesystem to support reading from and writing to S3 storage during a MapReduce job.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] There are also S3 filesystems for Linux, which mount a remote S3 filestore on an EC2 image, as if it were local storage.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] As S3 is not a full POSIX filesystem, things may not behave the same as on a local disk (e.g., no locking support).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon's elastic IP address feature is similar to static IP address in traditional data centers, with one key difference.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] A user can programmatically map an elastic IP address to any virtual machine instance without a network administrator's help and without having to wait for DNS to propagate the binding.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In this sense an Elastic IP Address belongs to the account and not to a virtual machine instance.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] It exists until it is explicitly removed, and remains associated with the account even while it is associated with no instance.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon CloudWatch is a web service that provides real-time monitoring to Amazon's EC2 customers on their resource utilization such as CPU, disk, network and replica lag for RDS Database replicas.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] CloudWatch does not provide any memory, disk space, or load average metrics without running additional software on the instance.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Since December 2017 Amazon provides a CloudWatch Agent for Windows and Linux operating systems included disk and previously not available memory information, previously Amazon provided example scripts for Linux instances to collect OS information.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The data is aggregated and provided through AWS management console.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] It can also be accessed through command line tools and Web APIs, if the customer desires to monitor their EC2 resources through their enterprise monitoring software.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon provides an API which allows clients to operate on CloudWatch alarms.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The metrics collected by Amazon CloudWatch enables the auto-scaling feature to dynamically add or remove EC2 instances.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The customers are charged by the number of monitoring instances.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Since May 2011, Amazon CloudWatch accepts custom metrics that can be submitted programmatically via Web Services API and then monitored the same way as all other internal metrics, including setting up the alarms for them, and since July 2014 Cloudwatch Logs service is also available.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Basic Amazon CloudWatch is included in Amazon Free Tier service.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon's auto-scaling feature of EC2 allows it to automatically adapt computing capacity to site traffic.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The schedule-based (e.g. time-of-the-day) and rule-based (e.g.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] CPU utilization thresholds) auto scaling mechanisms are easy to use and efficient for simple applications.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] However, one potential problem is that VMs may take up to several minutes to be ready to use, which are not suitable for time critical applications.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The VM startup time is dependent on image size, VM type, data center locations, etc.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The convenience of using EC2 enables you to dynamically increase capacity in accordance with demand and access resources rapidly.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On Demand EC2 instances are priced per hour.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] An example of this pricing would be $0.096 per hour for a Linux, m5.large, EC2 instance in the us-east-1 region.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Pricing will vary based on the instance type, region, and operating system of the instance.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Public on-demand pricing for EC2 can be found on the AWS website.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The other pricing models for EC2 have different pricing models.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Spot instances also have a cost per instance hour, but the cost will change on a regular basis based on the supply of EC2 spot capacity.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Reserved Instances and Compute Savings plans are priced per hour.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Each of these reservation tools has its own price per hour based on the payment option, term and reservation product being used.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] These prices are locked in for either a 1-year or 3-year term.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon EC2 price varies from $2.5 per month for "nano" instance with 1 vCPU and 0.5 GB RAM on board to "xlarge" type of instances with 32 vCPU and 488 GB RAM billed up to $3997.19 per month.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The charts above show how Amazon EC2 pricing is compared to similar Cloud Computing services: Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, Kamatera, and Vultr.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] To make EC2 more fault-tolerant, Amazon engineered *Availability Zones* that are designed to be insulated from failures in other availability zones.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Availability zones do not share the same infrastructure.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Applications running in more than one availability zone can achieve higher availability.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] EC2 provides users with control over the geographical location of instances that allows for latency optimization and high levels of redundancy.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] For example, to minimize downtime, a user can set up server instances in multiple zones that are insulated from each other for most causes of failure such that one backs up the other.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Higher-availability database services, like Amazon Relational Database Service run separately from EC2 instances.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] In early July 2008, the anti-spam organizations Outblaze and Spamhaus.org began blocking Amazon's EC2 address pool due to problems with the distribution of spam and malware.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On December 1, 2010, Amazon pulled its service to WikiLeaks after coming under political pressure in the US.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Assange said that WikiLeaks chose Amazon knowing it would probably be kicked off the service "in order to separate rhetoric from reality".
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The Internet group Anonymous attempted to attack EC2 in revenge; however, Amazon was not affected by the attack.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Amazon's websites were temporarily offline on December 12, 2010, although it was initially unclear if this was due to attacks or a hardware failure.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] An Amazon official later stated that it was due to a hardware failure.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Shortly before 5 am ET on April 21, 2011, an outage started at EC2's Northern Virginia data center that brought down several websites, including Foursquare, Springpad, Reddit, Quora, and Hootsuite.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Specifically, attempts to use Amazon's elastic-disk and database services hung, failed, or were slow.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Service was restored to some parts of the data center (three of four "availability zones" in Amazon's terms) by late afternoon Eastern time that day; problems for at least some customers were continuing as of April 25.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] 0.07% of EBS volumes in one zone have also been lost; EBS failures were a part of normal operation even before this outage and were a risk documented by Amazon, though the number of failures and the number of *simultaneous* failures may find some EC2 users unprepared.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] On Sunday August 6, 2011, Amazon suffered a power outage in one of their Ireland availability zones.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Lightning was originally blamed for the outage; however, on August 11, Irish energy supplier ESB Networks dismissed this as a cause, but at time of writing, could not confirm what the cause of the problem was.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The power outage raised multiple questions regarding Amazon's EBS infrastructure, which caused several bugs in their software to be exposed.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] The bugs resulted in some customers' data being deleted when recovering EBS volumes in a mid-write operation during the crash.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] August 8, 2011, saw another network connectivity outage of Amazon's Northern Virginia data center, knocking out the likes of Reddit, Quora, Netflix and FourSquare.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Another Northern Virginia data center outage occurred on October 22, 2012, from approximately 10 am to 4 pm PT.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Edmodo, Airbnb, Flipboard, Reddit, and other customers were affected.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-elastic-compute-cloud] Anonymous claimed responsibility, but Amazon denied this assertion.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Amazon S3 manages data with an object storage architecture which aims to provide scalability, high availability, and low latency with high durability.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] The basic storage units of Amazon S3 are objects which are organized into buckets.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Each object is identified by a unique, user-assigned key.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Buckets can be managed using the console provided by Amazon S3, programmatically with the AWS SDK, or the REST application programming interface.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Objects can be up to five terabytes in size.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Requests are authorized using an access control list associated with each object bucket and support versioning which is disabled by default.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Amazon S3 can be used to replace static web-hosting infrastructure with HTTP client-accessible objects, index document support, and error document support.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] The Amazon AWS authentication mechanism allows the creation of authenticated URLs, valid for a specified amount of time.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Every item in a bucket can also be served as a BitTorrent feed.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] The Amazon S3 store can act as a seed host for a torrent and any BitTorrent client can retrieve the file.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] This can drastically reduce the bandwidth cost for the download of popular objects.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] A bucket can be configured to save HTTP log information to a sibling bucket; this can be used in data mining operations.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Various User Mode File System (FUSE)–based file systems for Linux or other Unix-like operating systems can be used to mount an S3 bucket as a file system.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] The semantics of the Amazon S3 file system are not that of a POSIX file system, so the file system may not behave entirely as expected.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Implementations include Rclone and AWS's own Mountpoint for S3.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Amazon S3 offers nine different storage classes with different levels of durability, availability, and performance requirements.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] The Amazon S3 Glacier storage classes above are distinct from Amazon Glacier, which is a separate product with its own APIs.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] An object in S3 can be between 0 bytes and 5 TB.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] If an object is larger than 5 TB, it must be divided into chunks prior to uploading.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] When uploading, Amazon S3 allows a maximum of 5 GB in a single upload operation; hence, objects larger than 5 GB must be uploaded via the S3 multipart upload API.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] As of 2025, S3 stores 500 trillion objects, 100s of exabytes of data, serves 200 million requests per second, and peaks at about 1 petabyte per second in bandwidth.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] The broad adoption of Amazon S3 and related tooling has given rise to competing services based on the S3 API.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] These services use the standard programming interface but are differentiated by their underlying technologies and business models.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] A standard interface enables better competition from rival providers and allows economies of scale in implementation, among other benefits.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Users are not required to go directly to Amazon as several storage providers such as Cloudian, Backblaze B2, Wasabi offer S3-compatible storage with options of on-premises and private cloud deployments.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Several open-source implementations of S3-compatible object store servers can be self-hosted, such as Garage.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] IBM Cloud Object Storage also offers a cloud-based S3-compatible option of Object Storage.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] Amazon Web Services introduced Amazon S3 in 2006.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-s3] In November 2017, AWS added default encryption capabilities at bucket level.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:boto3-aws/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:boto3-aws/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] When uploading, downloading, or copying a file or S3 object, the AWS SDK for Python automatically manages retries and multipart and non-multipart transfers.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] The management operations are performed by using reasonable default settings that are well-suited for most scenarios.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] To handle a special case, the default settings can be configured to meet requirements.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] Configuration settings are stored in a `boto3.s3.transfer.TransferConfig` object.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] The object is passed to a transfer method (`upload_file`, `download_file`, etc.) in the `Config=` parameter.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] The remaining sections demonstrate how to configure various transfer operations with the `TransferConfig` object.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] Multipart transfers occur when the file size exceeds the value of the `multipart_threshold` attribute.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] The following example configures an `upload_file` transfer to be multipart if the file size is larger than the threshold specified in the `TransferConfig` object.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] The maximum number of concurrent S3 API transfer operations can be tuned to adjust for the connection speed.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] Set the `max_concurrency` attribute to increase or decrease bandwidth usage.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] To reduce bandwidth usage, reduce the value; to increase usage, increase it.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] Transfer operations use threads to implement concurrency.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] If thread use is disabled, transfer concurrency does not occur.
[src:boto3-aws/guide-s3] Accordingly, the value of the `max_concurrency` attribute is ignored.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Object storage systems allow retention of massive amounts of unstructured data in which data is written once and read once (or many times).
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Object storage is used for purposes such as storing objects like videos and photos on Facebook, songs on Spotify, or files in online collaboration services, such as Dropbox.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] One of the limitations with object storage is that it is not intended for transactional data, as object storage was not designed to replace NAS file access and sharing; it does not support the locking and sharing mechanisms needed to maintain a single, accurately updated version of a file.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Jim Starkey coined the term ***blob*** working at Digital Equipment Corporation to refer to opaque data entities.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] The terminology was adopted for Rdb/VMS.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] *Blob* is often humorously explained to be an abbreviation for *binary large object*.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] According to Starkey, this backronym arose when Terry McKiever, working in marketing at Apollo Computer felt that the term needed to be an abbreviation.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] McKiever began using the expansion *basic large object*.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] This was later eclipsed by the retroactive explanation of blobs as *binary large objects*.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] According to Starkey, "Blob don't stand for nothin'." Rejecting the acronym, he explained his motivation behind the coinage, saying, "A blob is the thing that ate Cincinnatti [*sic*], Cleveland, or whatever", referring to the 1958 science fiction film *The Blob*.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] In 1995, research led by Garth Gibson on Network-Attached Secure Disks first promoted the concept of splitting less common operations, like namespace manipulations, from common operations, like reads and writes, to optimize the performance and scale of both.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] In the same year, a Belgian company – FilePool – was established to build the basis for archiving functions.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Object storage was proposed at Gibson's Carnegie Mellon University lab as a research project in 1996.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Another key concept was abstracting the writes and reads of data to more flexible data containers (objects).
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Fine grained access control through object storage architecture was further described by one of the NASD team, Howard Gobioff, who later was one of the inventors of the Google File System.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Other related work includes the Coda filesystem project at Carnegie Mellon, which started in 1987, and spawned the Lustre file system.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] There is also the OceanStore project at UC Berkeley, which started in 1999 and the Logistical Networking project at the University of Tennessee Knoxville, which started in 1998.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] In 1999, Gibson founded Panasas to commercialize the concepts developed by the NASD team.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Seagate Technology played a central role in the development of object storage.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] This paper was proposed to INCITS T-10 (International Committee for Information Technology Standards) with a goal to form a committee and design a specification based on the SCSI interface protocol.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] This defined objects as abstracted data, with unique identifiers and metadata, how objects related to file systems, along with many other innovative concepts.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Anderson presented many of these ideas at the SNIA conference in October 1999.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] The presentation revealed an IP Agreement that had been signed in February 1997 between the original collaborators (with Seagate represented by Anderson and Chris Malakapalli) and covered the benefits of object storage, scalable computing, platform independence, and storage management.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] One of the design principles of object storage is to abstract some of the lower layers of storage away from the administrators and applications.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Thus, data is exposed and managed as objects instead of blocks or (exclusively) files.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Objects contain additional descriptive properties which can be used for better indexing or management.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Administrators do not have to perform lower-level storage functions like constructing and managing logical volumes to utilize disk capacity or setting RAID levels to deal with disk failure.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Object storage also allows the addressing and identification of individual objects by more than just file name and file path.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Object storage adds a unique identifier within a bucket, or across the entire system, to support much larger namespaces and eliminate name collisions.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Object storage explicitly separates file metadata from data to support additional capabilities.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Object storage provides programmatic interfaces to allow applications to manipulate data.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] At the base level, this includes Create, read, update and delete (CRUD) functions for basic read, write and delete operations.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Some object storage implementations go further, supporting additional functionality like object/file versioning, object replication, life-cycle management and movement of objects between different tiers and types of storage.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Most API implementations are REST-based, allowing the use of many standard HTTP calls.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] The vast majority of cloud storage available in the market leverages an object-storage architecture.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Some notable examples are Amazon S3, which debuted in March 2006, Microsoft Azure Blob Storage, IBM Cloud Object Storage, Rackspace Cloud Files (whose code was donated in 2010 to Openstack project and released as OpenStack Swift), and Google Cloud Storage released in May 2010.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Some distributed file systems use an object-based architecture, where file metadata is stored in metadata servers and file data is stored in object storage servers.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] File system client software interacts with the distinct servers, and abstracts them to present a full file system to users and applications.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Some early incarnations of object storage were used for archiving, as implementations were optimized for data services like immutability, not performance.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] EMC Centera and Hitachi HCP (formerly known as HCAP) are two commonly cited object storage products for archiving.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Another example is Quantum ActiveScale Object Storage Platform.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] More general-purpose object-storage systems came to market around 2008.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] A few object-storage systems support Unified File and Object storage, allowing clients to store objects on a storage system while simultaneously other clients store files on the same storage system.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Other vendors in the area of Hybrid cloud storage are using Cloud storage gateways to provide a file access layer over object storage, implementing file access protocols such as SMB and NFS.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Some large Internet companies developed their own software when object-storage products were not commercially available or use cases were very specific.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Facebook famously invented their own object-storage software, code-named Haystack, to address their particular massive-scale photo management needs efficiently.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Object storage at the protocol and device layer was proposed 20 years ago and approved for the SCSI command set nearly 10 years ago as "Object-based Storage Device Commands" (OSD), however, it had not been put into production until the development of the Seagate Kinetic Open Storage platform.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] The SCSI command set for Object Storage Devices was developed by a working group of the SNIA for the T10 committee of the International Committee for Information Technology Standards (INCITS).
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] T10 is responsible for all SCSI standards.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] One of the first object-storage products, Lustre, is used in 70% of the Top 100 supercomputers and ~50% of the Top 500.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] As of June 16, 2013, this includes 7 of the top 10, including the current fourth fastest system on the list - China's Tianhe-2 and the seventh fastest, the Titan supercomputer at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Object-storage systems had good adoption in the early 2000s as an archive platform, particularly in the wake of compliance laws like Sarbanes-Oxley.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] After five years in the market, EMC's Centera product claimed over 3,500 customers and 150 petabytes shipped by 2007.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Hitachi's HCP product also claims many petabyte-scale customers.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Newer object storage systems have also gotten some traction, particularly around very large custom applications like eBay's auction site, where EMC Atmos is used to manage over 500 million objects a day.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] As of March 3, 2014, EMC claims to have sold over 1.5 exabytes of Atmos storage.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] On July 1, 2014, Los Alamos National Lab chose the Scality RING as the basis for a 500-petabyte storage environment, which would be among the largest ever.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] "Captive" object storage systems like Facebook's Haystack have scaled impressively.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] In April 2009, Haystack was managing 60 billion photos and 1.5 petabytes of storage, adding 220 million photos and 25 terabytes a week.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Facebook more recently stated that they were adding 350 million photos a day and were storing 240 billion photos.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] This could equal as much as 357 petabytes.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Cloud storage has become pervasive as many new web and mobile applications choose it as a common way to store binary data.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] As the storage back-end to many popular applications like Smugmug and Dropbox, Amazon S3 has grown to massive scale, citing over 2-trillion objects stored in April 2013.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Two months later, Microsoft claimed that they stored even more objects in Azure at 8.5 trillion.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] By April 2014, Azure claimed over 20-trillion objects stored.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Windows Azure Storage manages Blobs (user files), Tables (structured storage), and Queues (message delivery) and counts them all as objects.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Coldago Research adopted qualitative and quantitative analysis of the object storage market to rank 13 notable vendors based on technological capabilities, market momentum, and innovation trajectory.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] The 2024 Coldago object storage market leader rating is in alphabetical order: Cloudian, DataCore, Dell EMC, Huawei, IBM, MinIO, Pure Storage, Quantum, and VAST Data.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] In the first version of the OSD standard, objects are specified with a 64-bit partition ID and a 64-bit object ID.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Partitions are created and deleted within an OSD, and objects are created and deleted within partitions.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] There are no fixed sizes associated with partitions or objects; they are allowed to grow subject to physical size limitations of the device or logical quota constraints on a partition.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] An extensible set of attributes describe objects.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Some attributes are implemented directly by the OSD, such as the number of bytes in an object and the modification time of an object.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] There is a special policy tag attribute that is part of the security mechanism.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Other attributes are uninterpreted by the OSD.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] These are set on objects by the higher-level storage systems that use the OSD for persistent storage.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] For example, attributes might be used to classify objects, or to capture relationships among different objects stored on different OSDs.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] A list command returns a list of identifiers for objects within a partition, optionally filtered by matches against their attribute values.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] A list command can also return selected attributes of the listed objects.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Read and write commands can be combined, or piggy-backed, with commands to get and set attributes.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] This ability reduces the number of times a high-level storage system has to cross the interface to the OSD, which can improve overall efficiency.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] A second generation of the SCSI command set, "Object-Based Storage Devices - 2" (OSD-2) added support for snapshots, collections of objects, and improved error handling.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] A snapshot is a point-in-time copy of all the objects in a partition into a new partition.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] The OSD can implement a space-efficient copy using copy-on-write techniques so that the two partitions share objects that are unchanged between the snapshots, or the OSD might physically copy the data to the new partition.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] The standard defines clones, which are writeable, and snapshots, which are read-only.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] A collection is a special kind of object that contains the identifiers of other objects.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] There are operations to add and delete from collections, and there are operations to get or set attributes for all the objects in a collection.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Collections are also used for error reporting.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] If an object becomes damaged by the occurrence of a media defect (i.e., a bad spot on the disk) or by a software error within the OSD implementation, its identifier is put into a special error collection.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] The higher-level storage system that uses the OSD can query this collection and take corrective action as necessary.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] The border between an object store and a key–value store is blurred, with key–value stores being sometimes loosely referred to as object stores.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] A traditional block storage interface uses a series of fixed size blocks which are numbered starting at 0.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Data must be that exact fixed size and can be stored in a particular block which is identified by its logical block number (LBN).
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Later, one can retrieve that block of data by specifying its unique LBN.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] With a key–value store, data is identified by a key rather than a LBN.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] A key might be "cat" or "olive" or "42".
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] It can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Data (called a value in this parlance) does not need to be a fixed size and also can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] One stores data by presenting the key and data (value) to the data store and can later retrieve the data by presenting the key.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] This concept is seen in programming languages.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Python calls them dictionaries, Perl calls them hashes, Java, Rust and C++ call them maps, etc.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Several data stores also implement key–value stores such as Memcached, Redis and CouchDB.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Object stores are similar to key–value stores in two respects.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] First, the object identifier or URL (the equivalent of the key) can be an arbitrary string.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Second, data may be of an arbitrary size.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] There are, however, a few key differences between key–value stores and object stores.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] First, object stores also allow one to associate a limited set of attributes (metadata) with each piece of data.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] The combination of a key, value, and set of attributes is referred to as an object.
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Second, object stores are optimized for large amounts of data (hundreds of megabytes or even gigabytes), whereas for key–value stores the value is expected to be relatively small (kilobytes).
[src:boto3-aws/object-storage] Finally, object stores usually offer weaker consistency guarantees such as eventual consistency, whereas key–value stores offer strong consistency.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] This guide details the steps needed to install or update the AWS SDK for Python.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] The SDK is composed of two key Python packages: Botocore (the library providing the low-level functionality shared between the Python SDK and the AWS CLI) and Boto3 (the package implementing the Python SDK itself).
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] Documentation and developers tend to refer to the AWS SDK for Python as “Boto3,” and this documentation often does so as well.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] To use Boto3, you first need to install it and its dependencies.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] Before installing Boto3, ensure you’re using Python 3.10 or later.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] For details on how to update your project from older versions of Python, see Migrating to Python 3.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] For information about how to get the latest version of Python, see the official Python documentation.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] This provides an isolated space for your installation that will avoid unexpected interactions with packages installed at the system level.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] Skipping this step may result in unexpected dependency conflicts or failures with other tools installed on your system.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] The latest development version of Boto3 is on GitHub.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] In addition to the default install of Boto3, you can choose to include the new AWS Common Runtime (CRT).
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] The AWS CRT is a collection of modular packages that serve as a new foundation for AWS SDKs.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] Each library provides better performance and minimal footprint for the functional area it implements.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] Using the CRT, SDKs can share the same base code when possible, improving consistency and throughput optimizations across AWS SDKs.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] When the AWS CRT is included, Boto3 uses it to incorporate features not otherwise available in the AWS SDK for Python.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] Before using Boto3, you need to set up authentication credentials for your AWS account using either the IAM Console or the AWS CLI.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] You can either choose an existing user or create a new one.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] For instructions about how to create a user using the IAM Console, see Creating IAM users.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] Once the user has been created, see Managing access keys to learn how to create and retrieve the keys used to authenticate the user.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] Alternatively, you can create the credentials file yourself.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] By default, its location is `~/.aws/credentials`.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] At a minimum, the credentials file should specify the access key and secret access key.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] Alternatively, you can pass a `region_name` when creating clients and resources.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] You have now configured credentials for the default profile as well as a default region to use when creating connections.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] See Configuration for in-depth configuration sources and options.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] Now that you have an `s3` resource, you can make send requests to the service.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] You can also upload and download binary data.
[src:boto3-aws/quickstart] Resources and Collections are covered in more detail in the following sections.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] A **software development kit** (**SDK**) is a collection of software development tools in one installable package.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] They facilitate the creation of applications by having a compiler, debugger and sometimes a software framework.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] They are normally specific to a hardware platform and operating system combination.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] To create applications with advanced functionalities such as advertisements, push notifications, etc., most application software developers use specific software development kits.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] Some SDKs are required for developing a platform-specific app.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] For example, the development of an Android app on the Java platform requires a Java Development Kit.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] For iOS applications (apps) the iOS SDK is required.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] For Universal Windows Platform the .NET Framework SDK might be used.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] There are also SDKs that add additional features and can be installed in apps to provide analytics, data about application activity, and monetization options.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] Some prominent creators of these types of SDKs include Google, Smaato, InMobi, and Facebook.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] An SDK can take the form of application programming interfaces in the form of on-device libraries of reusable functions used to interface to a particular programming language, or it may be as complex as hardware-specific tools that can communicate with a particular embedded system.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] Common tools include debugging facilities and other utilities, often presented in an integrated development environment.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] SDKs may include sample software and/or technical notes along with documentation, and tutorials to help clarify points made by the primary reference material.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] Platform SDKs may be distributed as multiple installable components rather than as a single monolithic package.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] For example, the Android SDK is composed of multiple packages required for app development, and its `sdkmanager` command-line tool can view, install, update and uninstall SDK packages.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] Microsoft's Windows SDK similarly includes platform headers, libraries, Windows Runtime metadata and build tools for developing Windows applications.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] SDKs often include licenses that make them unsuitable for building software intended to be developed under an incompatible license.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] For example, a proprietary SDK is generally incompatible with free software development, while a GNU General Public License'd SDK could be incompatible with proprietary software development, for legal reasons.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] However, SDKs built under the GNU Lesser General Public License are typically usable for proprietary development.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] In cases where the underlying technology is new, SDKs may include hardware.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] For example, AirTag's 2012 near-field communication SDK included both the paying and the reading halves of the necessary hardware stack.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] The average Android mobile app implements 15.6 separate SDKs, with gaming apps implementing on average 17.5 different SDKs.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] The most popular SDK categories for Android mobile apps are analytics and advertising.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] SDKs can be unsafe (because they are implemented within apps yet run separate code).
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] Malicious SDKs (with honest intentions or not) can violate users' data privacy, damage app performance, or even cause apps to be banned from Google Play or the App Store.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] New technologies allow app developers to control and monitor client SDKs in real time.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] Providers of SDKs for specific systems or subsystems sometimes substitute a more specific term instead of *software*.
[src:boto3-aws/software-development-kit] For instance, both Microsoft and Citrix provide a driver development kit for developing device drivers.
